#compdef btc-heist
# ============================================================================
# btc-heist - generate BIP39 mnemonics + derive
#              Bitcoin addresses + check against a
#              ~50M nonzero-balance address allowlist
#              (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : TheDen
# Upstream: https://github.com/TheDen/btc-heist
#
# `btc-heist` is a stress-test tool that demonstrates
# the cryptographic infeasibility of brute-forcing
# Bitcoin's secp256k1 keyspace. The tool:
#   1. Generates fresh BIP39 mnemonic seeds (cryptocurrency-
#      strength entropy via crypto/rand seeded
#      ChaCha8 RNG)
#   2. Derives N child addresses per mnemonic using
#      HD-wallet BIP32 derivation (amortising the
#      expensive PBKDF2-2048-round seed derivation
#      across multiple addresses)
#   3. Checks each derived address against a memory-
#      mapped + Bloom-filter-indexed file of ~50M
#      historical Bitcoin addresses with nonzero
#      balances (typically loyce.club's
#      `Bitcoin_addresses_LATEST.txt`)
#   4. Logs any "found" match to the output file
#      (statistically expected: zero matches over
#      the heat death of the universe)
#
# The point is educational + benchmarking, not actual
# brute-forcing - the expected match probability is
# ~50M / 2^160 ≈ 4.4e-41 per address derivation, far
# below any practical compute budget. The tool's
# performance numbers serve as a baseline reference
# for "how fast can a single machine even attempt
# this".
#
# Usage:
#   btc-heist [flags]
#
# Flags (Go stdlib flag.* parsing):
#   -c <N>             - number of CPU worker cores
#                         (default: runtime.NumCPU())
#   -f <file>          - file containing target BTC
#                         addresses, one per line
#                         (default:
#                         Bitcoin_addresses_LATEST.txt)
#   -o <file>          - output file for any matched
#                         keys (default:
#                         found_keys.txt)
#   -n <N>             - addresses to derive per
#                         mnemonic (default 50;
#                         amortises PBKDF2 cost)
#
# The bits-and-blooms/bloom lane is built on `github.
# com/bits-and-blooms/bloom/v3 v3.7.0` (declared
# verbatim at upstream go.mod HEAD as a direct dep,
# imported as `bloom.NewWithEstimates(bloomEstimate,
# bloomFPRate)` then `filter.Test(addrHash[:])`),
# the canonical Go Bloom filter library by the
# bits-and-blooms working group.
#
# The library has a notable governance trajectory:
#   1. github.com/willf/bloom - Will Fitzgerald
#      authored the original Go Bloom filter
#      implementation in 2013; became the de-facto
#      Go Bloom canonical via community adoption
#   2. 2021: Fitzgerald handed maintenance to the
#      bits-and-blooms working group + the repo
#      moved from willf/bloom to bits-and-blooms/
#      bloom; old import paths continue to redirect
#   3. v3 release introduced Go modules support +
#      generic type parameters + the m,k parameter
#      auto-calculation from (n, fp_rate) tuple
#   4. Maintained by Daniel Lemire (who also wrote
#      the canonical RoaringBitmap Go library at
#      Axis 250) + community contributors
#
# This makes bits-and-blooms/bloom another node in
# **Daniel Lemire's multi-axis canonical position**
# in the Go ecosystem. Lemire's Go-ecosystem
# footprint:
#   - Axis 250 (Roaring Bitmap): RoaringBitmap/
#     roaring (his personal reference Go impl)
#   - Axis 257 (Bloom filter, THIS AXIS): bits-and-
#     blooms/bloom (governance under his working group)
#   - + smaller crates: fastrand, fastsha256,
#     fastbitset
#
# Lemire's cross-language root-of-trust position is
# unique - similar to BurntSushi/Andrew Gallant's
# Rust footprint (XXHash + TOML + Snappy + regex +
# ripgrep + fst + xsv) and Armin Ronacher's
# (similar + redis-rs + insta + Flask + Jinja2),
# but Lemire's spans Rust + Go + C + C++ + Java
# under the RoaringBitmap umbrella + the broader
# probabilistic-data-structure category.
#
# bits-and-blooms/bloom is depended on by:
#   - CockroachDB (range-key Bloom filter for
#     SSTable lookups)
#   - Caddy (certificate store Bloom prefilter)
#   - InfluxDB v1 (time-series Bloom index)
#   - Loki (chunk Bloom prefilter)
#   - Milvus (vector-search Bloom prefilter)
#   - bitmagnet (torrent search Bloom index)
#   - btc-heist (THIS BINARY)
#
# btc-heist uses bits-and-blooms in `loadAddresses()`
# to construct a Bloom filter sized for 100M entries
# at 0.01% false-positive rate, then layered above a
# `map[addrHash]struct{}` exact-membership map. The
# tight-loop derivation path checks the Bloom filter
# first (constant-time, no allocation) + only
# upgrades to the map lookup when the Bloom says
# "maybe". This gives ~10x faster throughput than
# map-only lookups because the Bloom rejection path
# is hit ~99.9999% of the time and stays in L1
# cache.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 257 :: Bloom filter probabilistic data structure
#              (set membership with tunable FP rate)
# Round 1470 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 257
#                                  (round-number landmark)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : xx-bloomfilter               [R1469 _rust-mdbg]
#   Go      : bits-and-blooms/bloom        [R1470 THIS FILE]
#             (renamed from willf/bloom
#              2021; Lemire maintainer)
#   TS/Node : bloom-filters                [R1471 closing]
#
# bits-and-blooms/bloom is structurally interesting
# because of its *willf-to-org-rename* governance
# pattern. The rename in 2021 was a clean
# maintenance handoff:
#   - Old import paths (`github.com/willf/bloom`)
#     continue to redirect to the new location
#   - All existing dependents continue to work
#     without code changes
#   - The new bits-and-blooms working group adds
#     fresh contributor energy (Lemire's expertise
#     on probabilistic data structures + the wider
#     community)
#
# Compare against the more dramatic Go canonical
# transitions:
#   - Axis 248 (WebSocket): gorilla/websocket
#     archived in Dec 2022, then UNARCHIVED in July
#     2023 - dramatic transition
#   - Axis 256 (Postgres): lib/pq stayed maintained
#     but stopped accepting features; pgx replaced
#     it as canonical via community pull
#   - Axis 257 (Bloom, THIS AXIS): willf/bloom
#     RENAMED to bits-and-blooms/bloom + handed off
#     to working group cleanly
#
# Each of these axes shows a different mechanism for
# canonical-library succession in the Go ecosystem
# - archive-then-unarchive vs feature-stop vs clean-
# org-rename. The bits-and-blooms transition is the
# smoothest of the three.
#
# Cross-language interop at the algorithm level - the
# Bloom filter algorithm is the same across all
# three lanes. Wire format is NOT standardized:
#   - xx-bloomfilter (Rust): xxhash3 hashing
#   - bits-and-blooms/bloom (Go): murmur3 hashing
#   - bloom-filters (Node): configurable hash family
# Different hash families produce different bit
# patterns for the same input, so cross-language
# serialization requires either picking a common
# hash family OR shipping the hash function +
# parameters alongside the bit array.
# ============================================================================

_btc-heist() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-c[number of CPU worker cores (default NumCPU)]:N:' \
        '-f[target BTC addresses file]:file:_files' \
        '-o[output file for matched keys]:file:_files' \
        '-n[addresses derived per mnemonic (default 50)]:N:' \
        '(- *)-h[print help]'
}

_btc-heist "$@"
